node.contents: I want to avoid the constructor calling during object creation in java (either default constructor or user defined constructor) . Is it possible to avoid constructor calling during object creation???

astNode.text: I want to avoid the constructor calling during object creation in java (either default constructor or user defined constructor) . Is it possible to avoid constructor calling during object creation???

node.contents: Actually, its possible under some circumstances by using classes from the JVM implementation (which do not belong to the JRE API and are implemenation specific).

astNode.text: Actually, its possible under some circumstances by using classes from the JVM implementation (which do not belong to the JRE API and are implemenation specific).

node.contents: It should also be possible using sun.misc.Unsafe.allocateInstance() (Java7)

astNode.text: It should also be possible using sun.misc.Unsafe.allocateInstance() (Java7)

node.contents: Also, the constructor is apparently bypassed when using the clone()-method to create a copy of an object (and the class doesn't override clone to implement it different from the Object.clone() method).

astNode.text: Also, the constructor is apparently bypassed when using the clone()-method to create a copy of an object (and the class doesn't override clone to implement it different from the Object.clone() method).

node.contents: All of these possibilities come with strings attached and should be used carefully, if at all.

astNode.text: All of these possibilities come with strings attached and should be used carefully, if at all.

node.contents: Simply extract the intialization logic that you want to avoid into another method called init. You can not avoid calling exactly one constructor.

node.contents: No matter what pattern or strategy you use, at some point your will need to call a constructor if you want to create an object.

astNode.text: You can mock the constructors of a class. They will still be called, but not executed. For example, the following JUnit+JMockit test does that:

elements.contents: static class CodeUnderTest { private final SomeDependency someDep = new SomeDependency(123, "abc"); int doSomething(String s) { someDep.doSomethingElse(s); return someDep.getValue(); } } static final class SomeDependency { SomeDependency(int i, String s) { throw new RuntimeException("won't run"); } int getValue() { return -1; } } @Test public void mockEntireClassIncludingItsConstructors() { new NonStrictExpectations() { @Mocked SomeDependency mockDep; { mockDep.getValue(); result = 123; } }; int result = new CodeUnderTest().doSomething("testing"); assertEquals(123, result); }
